        <CONCLUSION> S is M </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Is S trying to mislead others about her/ his mental state? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Mental-World Claims. Physical-World Premiss: Effect </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> P </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> The fact that S is M is the best explanation for P </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> S is M </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Is anything else a good explanation of P? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Mental-World Claims. Regulative-Rule Premiss 1 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> A is obligatory (prohibited) </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> People generally accept the rules of the community </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> S believes that s/he must do (refrain from doing) A. </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Does S regard the rule as legitimate? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Mental-World Claims. Regulative-Rule Premiss 2 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> A is obligatory (prohibited)in society S </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> The fact that members of S believe that A is desiderable (undesiderable) conduct is the best explanation of the fact that A is obligatory (prohibited) </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> Memebrs of S believe that A is desiderable (undesiderable) conduct </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Does the majority really think that A is desiderable (undesiderable) conduct? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Constitutive-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss 1 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> A W is a D </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> Whenever expressions are referentially coextensive, they are synonymous. </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> "W" means the same as "D" </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Is the premiss a necessary truth? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Constitutive-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss 2 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> In the official rulebook of I (a rule-governed institution such a game, or a club, or a legal system), it is stated that D counts as W  </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> Official rulebooks correctly report the rules in force  </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> D counts as W </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Has the rule changed since the publication of the rulebook? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Constitutive-Rule claims: Mental-World Premiss </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> Speakers of L believe that "W" means the same as "D" </PREMISE>
