      </FORM>
      <CQ> Is S a special case of X's? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Regulative-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss and Enacted-Rule Conclusion 1 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> There is statute/enactment declaring that doing (failing to do) A is an offence punishable by... </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> Those who produced the enactment are officially empowered to create such rules </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> A is prohibited (obligatory) for those within the jurisdiction of the enactment </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Are there procedural deficiencies? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Regulative-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss and Enacted-Rule Conclusion 2 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> Being declared guilty of doing (failing to do) A in jurisdiction J results in censure /sanctions </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> Generally, official censure /sanctions arise from rule violations  </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> Doing (refraining from doing) A in jurisdiction J is prohibited </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Does the body/ group inflicting censure/ sanctions lack official standing? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Regulative-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss and Unenacted-Rule Conclusion 1 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> In society S people in situation C do (avoid) A </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> People generally conform to the rules in their society </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> In society S, doing A is obligatory (prohibited) in situation C </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Is doing (avoiding doing) A merely habitual? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Regulative-Rule claims: Physical-World Premiss and Unenacted-Rule Conclusion 2 </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> Members of S commonly censure/ apply sanctions to follow members when the latter do (fail to do) A </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> Unenacted rules are generally enforced by the community </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> A is prohibited (obligatory) in S </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
      <NAME> Arguments for Regulative-Rule claims: Mental-World Premiss and Unenacted-Rule Conclusion </NAME>
      <FORM>
        <PREMISE> Members of society/ group S believe that A is obligatory (prohibited) in situation C </PREMISE>
        <PREMISE> People are generally aware of the rules in their society/ group </PREMISE>
        <CONCLUSION> A is obligatory (prohibited) in situation C in society /group S </CONCLUSION>
      </FORM>
      <CQ> Are those who believe that A is obligatory (prohibited) typical of the membership of S? </CQ>
    </SCHEME>
    <SCHEME>
